<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the synthetic role assignment
    that grants the scoped role `x_casemgmt_case_viewer` to the synthetic demo
    user `x_casemgmt_demo_viewer`. This is one of exactly THREE role-assignment
    records in the case-management POC scoped application (the others grant
    the manager and agent roles to their respective demo personas).

    Persona role activated by this grant (per AAP Section 0.5.6 ACL Matrix):
      Once the Update Set commits, the demo viewer user holds the
      x_casemgmt_case_viewer role and therefore receives:
        - x_casemgmt_case        Read All; NO Create / NO Write / NO Delete
        - x_casemgmt_case_task   Read All; NO Create / NO Write / NO Delete
        - x_casemgmt_case_party  Read All; NO Create / NO Write / NO Delete
      Unlike the case_agent persona, the viewer's read scope is NOT
      restricted to "Assigned only" — the viewer reads every row in the
      three custom tables regardless of assigned_agent / assigned_group.
      Per AAP Section 0.5.5 (State-Machine Transition Map), the viewer has
      NO authority to drive any state transition; transition guards in the
      Flow Designer subflows implicitly reject viewer callers because the
      OnUpdate trigger fires only on records the caller can write, and
      viewers have no write privilege.

    Validation Gate 3 dependency (AAP Section 0.7.3):
      Per the gate's pass condition "case_viewer cannot write", the
      operator impersonates the demo viewer to verify all modification
      attempts (create, write, delete) are blocked by the ACLs while read
      access is preserved. Without THIS role-assignment record, the demo
      viewer holds no scoped role at all — making Gate 3's verification
      inconclusive (a denied write attempt could be due to no role grant
      rather than a properly enforced read-only ACL pattern). This file
      is therefore central to Gate 3 of the seven-row validation
      framework.

    Why this assignment record lives in the SCOPED Update Set even though
    `sys_user_has_role` is a global OOB table:
      The scoped Update Set's deliverable is fully self-contained: the
      reviewer must be able to install the Update Set on a fresh PDI and
      immediately exercise all seven validation gates. The three demo
      personas (manager, agent, viewer) are required by Gate 3 (ACL role-
      based access) and Gate 6 (dashboard rendering with synthetic data).
      Tracking the role-assignment records inside the scoped Update Set
      ensures they import together with the rest of the application; the
      scope binding via <sys_scope> and <sys_package> source attribute
      groups them with the scoped app even though their parent table
      (sys_user_has_role) is global. No global-scope WRITES are performed:
      only INSERTS into sys_user_has_role (a data table) — the OOB
      sys_user_has_role dictionary, ACLs, and form layouts are never
      modified.

    Authoring rules honored (per AAP Sections 0.7.1 / 0.7.2 and the agent
    prompt's eight authoring rules):

      Rule 1 — Synthetic Only:
        <user> resolves to `x_casemgmt_demo_viewer` — a fully synthetic
        demo persona created by ../users/sys_user_x_casemgmt_demo_viewer.xml
        with the unmistakably non-real first_name "Demo" and last_name
        "Viewer". <role> resolves to `x_casemgmt_case_viewer` — a brand-new
        scoped role defined by ../../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_viewer
        .xml. Both sides of this association are unmistakably non-real and
        live exclusively inside the x_casemgmt scope. NO real users (no
        admin, no system) and NO OOB roles (no itil, no snc_internal,
        no personalize_dictionary, no report_admin) are referenced.

      Rule 2 — Zero Hardcoded sys_id Cross-References:
        - The record's OWN <sys_id> below is THIS record's identity key
          (acceptable per AAP rule). It is a deterministic 32-character
          lowercase hex value (MD5 of the canonical
          "x_casemgmt_demo_viewer:x_casemgmt_case_viewer" tuple) so the
          Update Set engine resolves the same sys_id on every PDI,
          guaranteeing idempotent re-imports during round-trip
          verification.
        - The <user> reference resolves by display_value="x_casemgmt_demo_viewer"
          — the Update Set engine looks up sys_user.user_name = "x_casemgmt_demo_viewer"
          at apply time. The text-node value is the same lookup key (NOT
          a hardcoded sys_id literal) per the project convention used by
          every ACL <roles> field (e.g., ../../acl/x_casemgmt_case_read_viewer.xml
          uses <roles>x_casemgmt_case_viewer</roles> as a name lookup, not
          a sys_id literal).
        - The <role> reference resolves by display_value="x_casemgmt_case_viewer"
          — the Update Set engine looks up sys_user_role.name = "x_casemgmt_case_viewer"
          at apply time. The text-node value is the same lookup key.
        - The <sys_scope> and <sys_package> fields resolve by
          display_value / source attribute lookup against the scoped
          application's sys_scope record (../../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml,
          where <source>x_casemgmt</source>). The text-node value
          "x_casemgmt" is the scope's source key — the canonical project
          convention used by every other scoped artifact in the Update Set.

      Rule 3 — Scope Binding:
        <sys_scope> binds this assignment record to the scoped application
        whose source attribute is "x_casemgmt" (defined in
        ../../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml). The display_value attribute is
        "Case Management" — the human-readable scoped-app name. The
        <sys_package> follows the same pattern with the source attribute
        pointing at the scope source name. Although sys_user_has_role is
        a global OOB table, the SCOPED demo grant is tracked in the scoped
        Update Set so the deliverable is fully self-contained.

      Rule 4 — No Inheritance:
        <inherited>false</inherited> (literal lowercase string "false").
        Group-based role inheritance is NOT used in this POC; this is a
        direct user-to-role grant. If <inherited>true</inherited> were
        used, the platform would interpret this row as derivative of a
        parent group's role grant, which would be inconsistent with the
        canonical pattern. The demo viewer is also intentionally NOT a
        member of x_casemgmt_demo_team (only the demo agent is a member —
        see ../groups/sys_user_group_x_casemgmt_demo_team.xml), so even
        if group-level role inheritance were permitted, the viewer would
        not inherit anything from the group.

      Rule 5 — Active State:
        <state>active</state> (literal lowercase string "active"). The
        role assignment is effective immediately upon Update Set commit.
        Inactive states (requested, pending, expired) are workflow-
        related and not used in the POC seeding flow.

      Rule 6 — Idempotency Anchor:
        The record's idempotent key is the (user, role) tuple
        ("x_casemgmt_demo_viewer", "x_casemgmt_case_viewer"). The companion
        seed script ../../scripts/seed_demo_data.js's
        ensureRoleAssignment(DEMO.USERS.VIEWER, ROLES.VIEWER) helper
        queries by both fields BEFORE inserting; the action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE"
        attribute on the inner <sys_user_has_role> element provides the
        equivalent idempotency guarantee at Update Set commit time. These
        exact display_value strings MUST match the corresponding values
        in ../users/sys_user_x_casemgmt_demo_viewer.xml (<user_name> =
        "x_casemgmt_demo_viewer") and ../../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_viewer.xml
        (<name> = "x_casemgmt_case_viewer") — verified at authoring time.

      Rule 7 — Minimum Field Set:
        ONLY the four content fields required by the agent prompt's
        Mandatory Field Specification are populated: user, role,
        inherited, state. Plus the standard ServiceNow housekeeping
        (sys_class_name, sys_id, sys_scope, sys_package, sys_created_by,
        sys_update_name). All additional sys_user_has_role columns
        (granted_by, u_*, etc.) are auto-defaulted by the platform on
        first import. This keeps the file small, avoids dependencies on
        other global tables (no granted_by reference to another sys_user),
        and makes the record resilient to ServiceNow release-version
        drift across Yokohama / Zurich / Australia.

      Rule 8 — Scoped Update Set XML Conventions:
        Root element: <record_update table="sys_user_has_role">
        Inner element: <sys_user_has_role action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        for idempotent re-import per AAP Section 0.7.1 round-trip-
        verification.
        UTF-8 encoding declared in XML prolog.
        Boolean values lowercase: <inherited>false</inherited>.
        Element ordering: alphabetical (matching every other XML in the
        scoped Update Set).

    Cross-dependencies (per AAP Section 0.5.2):

      This grant DEPENDS ON (must be loaded BEFORE this record):
        - ../../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml (scoped app)
        - ../../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml (scope record - resolves
          sys_scope and sys_package source="x_casemgmt")
        - ../users/sys_user_x_casemgmt_demo_viewer.xml (the demo viewer
          user — resolves <user> by user_name lookup)
        - ../../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_viewer.xml (the scoped
          role — resolves <role> by name lookup)

      Records that DEPEND ON this grant (loaded AFTER this record):
        - The 3 read-only ACL records at ../../acl/x_casemgmt_case_read_viewer.xml,
          ../../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_read_viewer.xml,
          ../../acl/x_casemgmt_case_party_read_viewer.xml — the viewer's
          read privileges on all three scoped tables are encoded in these
          ACLs and are activated for the demo viewer via this grant.
        - Validation Gate 3 (ACLs) testing — the operator impersonates
          the demo viewer to verify that all cases are READABLE while
          create / write / delete attempts are blocked.
        - Person-type demo party records at ../parties/x_casemgmt_case_party_demo_*.xml
          where the demo viewer is referenced as the `person` field on
          case 05's Requester party — although the person reference
          resolves regardless of role grants, validation tests will
          impersonate the viewer to read case 05 and confirm Person-type
          parties display the linked sys_user's display_value.

    Source-side semantic reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported)
    per AAP Sections 0.8.1 and 0.7.1:
      - acm-services/acm-service-users/src/main/java/com/armedia/acm/
        services/users/model/ApplicationRolesConfig.java
        Holds `application.roles` as List<String> bound from external
        configuration via @ListValue("application.roles") and exposes
        MERGE_APPLICATION_ROLES_OP = "application.~roles". Semantic
        reference for ArkCase's role-list configuration model. ArkCase's
        mechanism (config-driven `application.roles` list bound to user
        → role mappings via RolesPrivilegesService) is replaced in the
        target by this OOB ServiceNow sys_user_has_role join-table row
        authored fresh — there is no field-by-field mapping from ArkCase's
        Java model to sys_user_has_role.
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-admin-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/admin/service/RolesPrivilegesService.java
        Central CRUD / normalization service for ArkCase role / privilege
        management. ArkCase normalizes role names by uppercasing,
        replacing whitespace with underscores, replacing periods with
        double-underscores, and prepending ROLE_PREFIX = "ROLE_". The
        ServiceNow target replaces this normalization with the scope-
        prefix convention (x_casemgmt_); the ROLE_ prefix is intentionally
        NOT used. Per AAP Section 0.7.1 ("API-compatibility preservation
        is explicitly NOT required"), the ArkCase role-assignment
        infrastructure (Spring service classes, REST controllers under
        /api/v1/plugin/admin/... and /api/latest/plugin/admin/...) is
        explicitly NOT replicated.

    Validation hooks (per the agent prompt):
      - XML well-formedness check using xmllint in its no-output mode
        returns zero errors.
      - The standard no-PII grep targeting common consumer first-name
        and surname patterns plus consumer-email-domain TLD patterns
        returns zero matches in the actual data fields of this record;
        the synthetic identifiers used here (the demo persona user_name
        and the scoped role name) do not include any PII tokens.
      - The standard no-extra-fields grep targeting the granted_by
        element name and the custom-prefix element name pattern returns
        zero matches; neither the granted_by element nor any custom-
        prefixed element is populated on this record.
      - Cross-reference resolution: the display_value="x_casemgmt_demo_viewer"
        value matches the <user_name>x_casemgmt_demo_viewer</user_name>
        value in ../users/sys_user_x_casemgmt_demo_viewer.xml exactly; the
        display_value="x_casemgmt_case_viewer" value matches the
        <name>x_casemgmt_case_viewer</name> value in
        ../../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_viewer.xml exactly.
      - The concrete scope identifier `casemgmt` is used per AAP convention; the same identifier is used in every cross-reference at
        App Engine Studio creation time,. The same identifier is used consistently across every artifact in this scoped application.
-->
<record_update table="sys_user_has_role">
    <sys_user_has_role action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <inherited>false</inherited>
        <role display_value="x_casemgmt_case_viewer">x_casemgmt_case_viewer</role>
        <state>active</state>
        <sys_class_name>sys_user_has_role</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_id>b095d91833fde26d96f511e6a60afd58</sys_id>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_casemgmt">x_casemgmt</sys_package>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_casemgmt</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_user_has_role_x_casemgmt_demo_viewer</sys_update_name>
        <user display_value="x_casemgmt_demo_viewer">x_casemgmt_demo_viewer</user>
    </sys_user_has_role>
</record_update>
